wrote yesterday that memecoins have become the main line of US crypto =0Ain=
 part because, unlike more useful crypto ideas, they avoid scrutiny from th=
e =0AUS Securities and Exchange Commission. =E2=80=9CMemecoins areobviously=
 not securities,=E2=80=9D =0AI wrote; =E2=80=9Cthey areobviously not =E2=80=
=98an investment of money in a common enterprise =0Awith profits to come so=
lely from the efforts of others,=E2=80=99 because there are no =0Aenterpris=
e, no profits and no efforts.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AI think that is right, but a re=
ader pointed out that some lawyers disagree, =0Aand have made a business of=
 suing memecoin promoters for doing unregistered =0Asecurities offerings.He=
re=E2=80=99s one <> against =E2=80=9Cthe =E2=80=98Hawk Tuah Girl,=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D whose =0Amemecoin we havediscussed previously <>: =0A=0AAt the he=
art of the lawsuit is the allegation that the $HAWK token constitutes =0Aan=
 unregistered security. The complaint states, =E2=80=9C[t]he $HAWK Token ex=
hibits all =0Athe characteristics of an unregistered security under establi=
shed legal =0Aprecedent.=E2=80=9D The plaintiffs argue that the defendants =
leveraged Haliey Welch=E2=80=99s =0Acelebrity status to create =E2=80=9Ca s=
peculative frenzy that caused the [$HAWK] =0AToken=E2=80=99s market value t=
o spike shortly after launch, reaching a significant =0Amarket capitalizati=
on.=E2=80=9D As alleged in the complaint, the defendants engaged in =0Aacti=
ons that potentially violated federal securities laws. The lawsuit claims =
=0Athat the $HAWK token exhibits characteristics of an unregistered securit=
y, and =0Awas offered and sold to the public without proper registration wi=
th the SEC.=0A=0AThe important lesson of this column is that everything is =
securities fraud, =0Aincluding the things that I don=E2=80=99t think are se=
curities fraud.=0A=0ASecond <>:=0A=0AThe leader of one of Africa=E2=80=99s =
poorest nations has mimicked Donald Trump with =0Athe launch of a so-called=
 memecoin, only to see its value immediately crash =0Aover concerns the pro=
ject was an elaborate fake.=0A=0AFaustin-Archange Touad=C3=A9ra, president =
of the Central African Republic, said on =0AX that the country=E2=80=99s me=
mecoin was =E2=80=9Can experiment designed to show how something =0Aas simp=
le as a meme can unite people, support national development and put CAR =0A=
on the world stage in a unique way=E2=80=9D. =E2=80=A6=0A=0AThe $CAR memeco=
in=E2=80=99s value has plunged 95 per cent since trading began early on =0A=
Monday, hitting around $0.04 on Tuesday. The token has a market capitalisat=
ion =0Aof $37mn, according to data provider CoinMarketCap, down from a shor=
tlived peak =0Aof $350mn.=0A=0AYes look if you are a country you should def=
initely launch a memecoin=3F A =0Amemecoin is, like, sovereign debt with no=
 maturity, no interest and no =0Ainflationary effect: You just sell it for =
money and then forget about it. =0AWhat=E2=80=99s not to like=3F=0A=0AThird=
: Someone launched a =E2=80=9CMoney Stuff by Matt Levine (MONEYSTUFF)=E2=80=
=9D coin on =0Apump.fun <>, the main site for memecoins. When I checked thi=
s morning it had a =0Amarket capitalization of about $5,700, which, uh. It =
should go without saying =0Athat (1) I didn=E2=80=99t launch this coin, (2)=
 I don=E2=80=99t own any of it and (3) you =0Ashould not buy it.=0A=0A=0AA =
new kind of financial adviser=0A=0AThis kind <>:=0A=0AUnlike most rich clie=
nts, who seek out financial advisors in the hope of =0Agetting even richer,=
 the 18- to 35-year-olds at the Making Money Make Change =0Aconference in N=
ashville are here to do the opposite. As the children of =0Amillionaires an=
d billionaires, they are among the heirs to the greatest wealth =0Atransfer=
 in American history =E2=80=94 some $16 trillion that will be passed down i=
n =0Athe next decade alone. And they don't want it. =E2=80=A6=0A=0AThose at=
tending the conference say they have found it surprisingly difficult =0Ato =
figure out how to divest themselves of their money. Depending on how their =
=0Atrust funds are set up, accessing their funds might require them to go t=
hrough =0Atheir family or a trustee, who often have a vested interest in ke=
eping the =0Amoney locked up for generations to come. "The trustees are lik=
e, 'What about =0Ayour children's children=3F'" Meg recalls being asked. "A=
nd we're like, 'What =0Aabout everybody else's children=3F'"=0A=0AWhat's mo=
re, the personal-finance industry is predicated on building wealth, =0Anot =
getting rid of it. "Almost all of my clients are really frustrated with the=
 =0Afinancial team that they come in with," says Iris Brilliant, a money co=
ach who =0Aworks with heirs to redistribute their wealth. Originally a poet=
ry major, =0ABrilliant worked as an organizer at Resource Generation for fi=
ve years before =0Alaunching her own practice. Now she's overwhelmed by the=
 demand for her =0Aservices. "There is a huge blossoming of interest, and I=
 have a waitlist for =0Aindividual coaching," she says. "I imagine that's t=
he case for a lot of my =0Apeers."=0A=0AI love capitalism, and probably my =
favorite kind of capitalism =E2=80=94 really the =0Amain thing I write abou=
t around here =E2=80=94 is the kind where you relieve people of =0Atheir mo=
ney and make them feel good about it. This is perhaps the most =0Atranspare=
nt way to do that: financial advisers who help heirs give away all =0Atheir=
 money.=0A=0ANo, just kidding, not all their money. That=E2=80=99s just mar=
keting. Really:=0A=0AGiven all the "Tax the Rich" and "Liberation" T-shirts=
 they're wearing, you =0Awouldn't guess that the people at the conference p=
ossess a combined net worth =0Aof at least $246 million. And that's not inc=
luding the wealth they stand to =0Ainherit from their families =E2=80=94 so=
me $1.5 billion, a "money survey" completed by =0Aall but seven of the atte=
ndees found. =E2=80=A6=0A=0ABy the end of the conference, 35 heirs have ple=
dged to redistribute a total of =0A$9.2 million.=0A=0AThat=E2=80=99s roughl=
y 3.7% of their combined wealth=3F You can get like 4.3% in a money =0Amark=
et fund.=0A=0A=0AThings happen=0A=0ATrump Curbs Enforcement of Antibribery =
Law <>. Goldman Sachs Abandons IPO =0ADiversity Pledge <> With US DEI Goals=
 Under Fire. Proxy Adviser ISS Kills  =0ADiversity Criteria <> for Assessin=
g Boards. Deloitte asks consultants to US =0Agovernment toremove gender pro=
nouns <> from emails. Powell Says Law Doesn=E2=80=99t =0AAllow Trump toFire=
 Fed Board <>. JPMorgan Defector Aims to Make Wells Fargo <> =0Aa Wall Stre=
et Force.Credit Quants <> Target Bulk Trades to Conquer $8 Trillion =0AMark=
et. Shopify takes downYe website selling swastika shirts <> after Super =0A=
Bowl ad. Behind the Scenes at the WestminsterDog Show <>.=0A=0AIf you'd lik=
e to get Money Stuff in handy email form, right in your inbox, =0Apleasesub=
scribe at this link <>. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other =0Agr=
eat Bloomberg newslettershere <>. Thanks!=0A=0A[1] Are these comparisons un=
fair=3F Musk's lawyer's statement says: "At x.AI, we =0Alive by the values =
I was promised OpenAI would follow. We=E2=80=99ve made Grok open =0Asource,=
 and we respect the rights of content creators. ... It=E2=80=99s time for O=
penAI =0Ato return to the open-source, safety-focused force for good it onc=
e was. We =0Awill make sure that happens.=E2=80=9D He's got a case that he'=
s the *most* charitable =0Aoption.=0A=0A[2] I should say: Everyone, includi=
ng me and Sam Altman, assumes that Musk =0Awill not actually buy OpenAI. Bu=
t =E2=80=A6 I mean, he would do it for $97.4 billion, =0Ano=3F Like that=E2=
=80=99s an incredible bargain=3F If he bought the nonprofit=E2=80=99s contr=
olling =0Astake for $97.4 billion, he=E2=80=99d control the business. OpenA=
I-the-nonprofit wants =0Ato give up control of the business, because that w=
ill help with fundraising, =0Abut Musk wouldn=E2=80=99t. Musk would pay $97=
.4 billion to get control of a $260 =0Abillion-ish business. He=E2=80=99d =
have minority shareholders (or =0Aweird-profit-interest-holders), but he co=
uld deal with them. And he=E2=80=99d have no =0Atrouble with fundraising.=
=0A=0A[3] Also a larger percentage ownership for the nonprofit might be off=
-putting =0Ato investors even outside of worries about cutting back their o=
wn stake. A, =0Asay, 40% nonprofit ownership would mean (1) more overhang (=
more shares to be =0Asold eventually) and (2) more *control* for the nonpro=
fit, which might make the =0Afor-profit investors nervous. The nonprofit co=
ntrol has not always been good =0Afor valuation <>.=0A=0A[4] Exercise for t=
he reader: If Musk, through xAI, buys OpenAI, is that =0Apositive or negati=
ve forthe credit of X <>=3F =0A=0A[5] Down here in a footnote I am just goi=
ng to throw out there that, if Bill =0AAckman doesn=E2=80=99t launch a host=
ile bid for Harvard in the next couple of years, =0AI=E2=80=99ll be a littl=
e disappointed.=0A=0A[6] Disclosure, I used to work at Goldman, though this=
